name: Acute Flaccid Paralysis
category: moh,front
case_def: Any case of acute flaccid paralysis occurs less than 15 years for a child, including Guillan-Barre syndrome or inflammation of the spinal cord or any other reason or any case of a doctor suspected cases of polio, regardless of age
risk_factors: Age (children under 5), contaminated water sources, another case of AFP reported in the same area
symptoms: Asymptomatic, fever, fatigue, headache, vomiting, stiffness in the neck, pain in limbs
labs_diagnostics: Stool sample taken 24 hours apart within 14 days of onset of paralysis

name: Measles
category: moh,front
case_def: Any person suffering from heat rash or with the doctor suspected measles
risk_factors: Age (children between 9 months and 5 years), overcrowding conditions, measles immunization coverage rate known to be <80% in area of origin/residence, malnutrition
symptoms: High fever, rash, runny nose, cough, conjunctivitis, Koplik spots (small white spots on buccal mucosa), red maculopapular (blotchy) rash 3 to 7 days after onset starting behind the ears and hairline
labs_diagnostics: Blood sample within 28 days of the onset of the rash and a sample of oral fluid to isolate the virus

name: German measles (Rubella)
category: moh,front
case_def: Any person suffering from heat rash or with the doctor suspected Rubella
risk_factors: Exposure to individual with suspected rubella or cold-like symptoms and rash
symptoms: Low-grade fever, Headache, Malaise, Mild coryza, Conjunctivitis, Postauricular, occipital and posterior cervical lymphadenopathy, Rash, Arthralgia, Arthritis, Thrombocytopenic purpura, Encephalitis
labs_diagnostics: Blood sample within 28 days of the onset of the rash and a sample of oral fluid to isolate the virus

name: Cholera
category: moh,front
case_def: Any person 2 years or older with acute diarrhoea (3 or more abnormally loose or fluid stools in the past 24 hours), with or without dehydration in an area where there is a cholera outbreak.
risk_factors: Contaminated water sources, contaminated food sources, cholera outbreak
symptoms: Watery diarrhea (3 or more abnormally loose or fluid stools in the past 24 hours, "rice-water" stool with or without vomiting), severe dehydration (including any of the following loss of skin turgor, malaise, tachypnoea, hypotension), fever (more cdon in children)
labs_diagnostics: Isolation of vibrio cholera 01 or 0139 from stool sample (at least 5 grams or pea sized) or rectal swab

name: Hepatitis A
category: moh,front
case_def: Any person with acute onset of jaundice (yellowing of whites of eyes or skin or dark/brown urine) AND severe illness with or without fever AND the absence of any known precipitating factors
risk_factors: Endemic Hepatitis A, contaminated water sources, contaminated food sources
symptoms: Asymptomatic, jaundice, dark urine, anorexia, malaise, extreme fatigue, pain in upper right quadrant
labs_diagnostics: Sporadic cases of acute jaundice with no or moderate fever are generally due to acute viral hepatitis (Hepatitis A, B, C or E), especially in children and young adults. Careful clinical examination can detect other causes of jaundice requiring specific treatment.

name: Hepatitis B
category: moh,front
case_def: Any person with acute onset of jaundice (yellowing of whites of eyes or skin or dark/brown urine) AND severe illness with or without fever AND the absence of any known precipitating factors
risk_factors: Endemic Hepatitis A, contaminated water sources, contaminated food sources
symptoms: Asymptomatic, jaundice, dark urine, anorexia, malaise, extreme fatigue, pain in upper right quadrant
labs_diagnostics: Sporadic cases of acute jaundice with no or moderate fever are generally due to acute viral hepatitis (Hepatitis A, B, C or E), especially in children and young adults. Careful clinical examination can detect other causes of jaundice requiring specific treatment.

name: Hepatitis C
category: moh,front
case_def: Any person with acute onset of jaundice (yellowing of whites of eyes or skin or dark/brown urine) AND severe illness with or without fever  AND the absence of any known precipitating factors
risk_factors: Endemic Hepatitis A, contaminated water sources, contaminated food sources
symptoms: Asymptomatic, jaundice, dark urine, anorexia, malaise, extreme fatigue, pain in upper right quadrant
labs_diagnostics: Sporadic cases of acute jaundice with no or moderate fever are generally due to acute viral hepatitis (Hepatitis A, B, C or E), especially in children and young adults. Careful clinical examination can detect other causes of jaundice requiring specific treatment.

name: Meningicoccal meningitis
category: moh,front
case_def:
A person with sudden onset of fever (>38.0 degrees Celsius axillary or >38.5 degrees Celsius rectal) 
and one of the following signs: 
 •  neck stiffness
 •  altered consciousness
 •  petechial or purpural rash, or other meningeal signs
risk_factors: Close and prolonged contact with individual suspected of having meningitis, High rates of acute respiratory infection (ARI), Overcrowding conditions, Other
symptoms: Sudden onset of intense headache, Suddepn onset of fever, Sudden onset of nausea, Sudden onset of vomiting, Sudden onset of photophobia, Sudden onset of stiff neck, Lethargy, Delirium, Coma, Purpura, Shock symptoms, Other
labs_diagnostics: Conduct lumbar puncture of first 25 cases during an epidemic to confirm diagnosis and serogroup

name: Bloody diarrhoea
category: moh,front
case_def: Diarrhoea associated with blood and which can be seen with the naked eye
risk_factors: Contaminated water, contaminated food, malnourished, age (children under 5, older adults), children who have had measles in past 6 weeks, shigellosis outbreak
symptoms: Malnourished, bloody diarrhea (3 or more abnormally loose or fluid stools in past 24 hours with visible blood), fever, abdominal cramps, rectal pain, seizures, sepsis, rectal prolapsed, toxic megacolon, hemolytic uraemic syndrome
labs_diagnostics: Cultivation of faecal sample in public health laboratories

name: Malaria
category: moh,front
case_def:
Any case suffering from fever accompanied by chills continuous or intermittent and sweating and pain in muscles and joints, headache and eye or vomiting and diarrhea in varying proportions in addition to the possibility of exposure to infection with malaria through travel to the infected area or accidentally by injection or be causing all imported.
OR Laboratory examination proves the existence of the malaria parasite in the blood, regardless of whether or not the symptoms of malaria.
OR the appearance of any of the following signs or clinical laboratory (parasite density in the blood of more than a hundred thousand parasite / Micron liter of blood, severe anemia, jaundice, lack of control Disorientation, convulsions, coma, exit hemoglobin in the urine, bleeding automatic, lung edema or shock
risk_factors: Exposure to areas where mosquito vector is present, Stagnant water sources, Movement to/from malaria endemic areas, Children, Pregnant woman, Immune compromised individuals, Malnutrition
symptoms: Fever, Anaemia, Single organ failure, Multiple organ failure, Respiratory distress, Chest pain, Severe abdominal pain, Neck pain, Severe headache, Unconscious or repeated convulsions, Compromised circulation
labs_diagnostics: Blood smear or rapid diagnostic malaria test

name: Pulmonary TB
category: moh,front
case_def: Any person with symptoms or signs of disease pulmonary tuberculosis, certain cough for a long time (more than two weeks), coughing up blood, chest pain, shortness of breath, fever / night sweats, fatigue, loss of weight
risk_factors: Crowded living conditions, exposure to someone with known TB, exposure to high prevalence area with TB, HIV-positive
symptoms: Cough of long duration (>2 weeks), coughing blood, chest pain, shortness of breath, fever/night sweats, tiredness, loss of appetite, weight loss
labs_diagnostics:
3 sputum examined by light microscopic (early morning sample are more likely to contain TB organism)
OR Chest X-ray

name: Non-pulmonary TB

name: HIV
category: moh,front
case_def: Case must be confirmed by a laboratory test
risk_factors: Unprotected vaginal and/or anal sex, sharing of drug injection equipment, breastfeeding with unknown or HIV-positive status
symptoms: See link for WHO HIV staging
labs_diagnostics: For adults and children 18 months and older, persons have a positive HIV antibody test (rapid or laboratory-based enzyme immunoassay) confirmed by a second HIV antibody test (rapid or laboratory-based enzyme immunoassay) relying on different antigens or of different operating characteristics. For children younger than 18 months, a positive virological test for HIV or its components (HIV-RNA or HIV-DNA or ultrasensitive HIV p24 antigen) confirmed by a second virological test obtained from a separate determination taken more than 4 weeks after birth.

name: Syphilis
category: moh,front
case_def:
Possible case includes the existence of clinically ulcer is often painful and bleeding and her pervasive base, may appear after ten days to three months of private sexual practices of exposure, and positive VDRL
Confirmed case identified by clinical examination and laboratory through a sample of the ulcer scan the dark field microscope

name: Gonorrhoea
category: moh,front
case_def:
Possible case includes yellow or white discharg,  burning when urinating or during intercourse, or burning and itching and discharge
Confirmed case identified through isolatation of bacteria on laboratory examination

name: Leishmaniasis
category: moh,front
case_def:
Suspected case: any person suffering from the presence of clinical signs of skin injury is slow to develop (Papule, Nodule or skin ulceration) and last for several weeks and may heal automatically after several months, leaving a permanent scar.
Possible case: anyone suspected such situation and be linked epidemiologically in terms of space and time with the leather case for the laboratory of L. installed.
Confirmed case: anyone such as suspected or potential case and prove the existence of leishmaniasis parasite in the laboratory sample taken from a skin infection.
risk_factors: Exposure to sand flies, Malnutrition, Poor housing and sanitation facilities, Population movement
symptoms: Lesions on mucous membranes in the nose, mouth, throat cavities and surrounding tissues
labs_diagnostics: Sample take directly from the skin, cultivation by PCR Laboratory test

name: Diphtheria
category: moh,front
case_def: Clinical signs for diphtheria including  airway obstruction, myocarditis or inflammation of the nervous during the period of 1-6 weeks of the start of symptoms, exposure to the case of diphtheria during the last two weeks, the existence of an epidemic of diphtheria in the region and exception other similar diseases that give similar symptoms by lab tests
risk_factors: Exposure to a case of diphtheria
symptoms: Fever, Running nose, Cough, Adherent membrane (tough, grayish-white color) of the nose, pharynx, tonsils or larynx, Inflammation of cervical lymph nodes and surrounding tissue
labs_diagnostics: Isolation of Corynebacterium diphtheria from the nose or throat OR histopathologic diagnosis of diphtheria OR an epidemiologic linkage to a laboratory-confirmed case of diphtheria

name: Tetanus
category: moh,front
case_def:
A person with at least one of the following signs inability to open the mouth or sustained spasm of the facial muscles or painful muscular contractions. 
Tetanus requires an injury or wound, but patients may be unable to recall a specific event
risk_factors: Injury or wound, potential unsterile cord cutting (pregnant women during delivery)
symptoms: Inability to open mouth, sustained spasm of the facial muscles including the jaw, painful muscular contractions, inability to breastfeed (newborn), stiff body or arch (newborn), inability to breathe
labs_diagnostics: Refer to MoH guidelines

name: Neonatal Tetanus
category: moh,front
case_def: Newborn baby with the following symptoms: breastfed in the first two days of old, symptoms appear between 3-28 days of old and inability to breastfeeding followed by muscle stiffness with or without cramps or both

name: Pertussis
category: moh,front
case_def: Clinical signs for whooping cough including continuous cough usually followed by a period without breathing and cyanosis stop, bleeding under the conjunctiva, exposure to a suspected case of whooping cough during the last 2-4 weeks
risk_factors: Exposure to a case of pertussis
symptoms: Cough lasting at least 2 weeks, paroxysms of coughing, inspiratory whoop,posttussive vomiting
labs_diagnostics: White blood cells are lymphocytes (15,000) or more per cubic milliliter

name: Anthrax
category: moh,front
case_def: Occupational hazards, where workers are dealing with animal skins and wool (especially goats) and bone products also affects veterinarians and agricultural workers
risk_factors: Skin lesion (cut, abrasion, bite, etc.) that could allow anthrax spore to penetrate, ingestion of contaminated meat, suspected inhalation of anthrax spores
symptoms:
Cutaneous anthrax: pimple/papule with or without surrounding vesicles, oedema, eschar

Gastrointestinal anthrax: nausea, vomiting, fever, abdominal pain, haematemesis, bloody diarrhea, massive ascites, toxaemia and shock, sore throat, dysphagia, fever, regional lymphadenopathy in the neck and toxaemia

Pulmonary (inhalation) anthrax: mild fever, fatigue, malaise, headache, muscle ache, chills and fever, dyspnea, cyanosis, disorientation with coma
labs_diagnostics: Demonstration of B. anthracis in a clinical specimen by microscopic examination of stained smears of vesicular fluid, blood, cerebrospinal fluid, pleural fluid, stool, etc. AND/OR isolation of B. anthracis from a clinical specimen (e.g. blood, lesions, discharges) AND/OR positive serology (ELISA, Western blot, toxin detection, chromatographic assay, fluorescent antibody test (FAT))

name: Rabies
category: moh,front
case_def:
Possible case: person exposed to an animal bite or touched an animal with suspected rabies and he showed symptoms of rabies during a period ranging from several days to several weeks
Confirmed case: person subjected to bite an animal or touched an animal with suspected rabies and he showed symptoms of rabies during a period ranging from several days to several weeks, including a phobia of water (Hydrophobia) and led to his death and tested positive for examination laboratory sample of brain after death
risk_factors: Exposure to rabies-carrying vectors (e.g. bats, etc.)
symptoms: Spasms in response to tactile, auditory, visual or olfactory stimuli, Paralysis or Guillan-Barre-like syndrome, Myoedema at percussion sites, Encephalitis
labs_diagnostics: RFFIT or FAVN test antibody tests for non-vaccinated patients

name: Food Poisoning
category: moh,front
case_def:
A person who ingests food or other agents that causes an infectious or toxic nature primarily of the gastrointestinal tract, but can include other systems (e.g. neurological, immunological). Probable cases have typical clinical symptoms of the illness without laboratory confirmation.  Suspected cases have fewer or atypical clinical symptoms.

•  Exclusion:
 •  acute watery diarrhoea (suspected cholera)
 •  bloody diarrhoea (suspected shigellosis)
 •  acute jaundice syndrome (suspected Hepatitis)
risk_factors: Consumption of contaminated food, Consumption of contaminated water
symptoms: Nausea, Vomiting, Mucoid diarrhoea (fatty stools), Other diarrhoea (non-watery and non-bloody type), Abdominal pain, Headache, Dizziness, Loss of consciousness, Coma, Thirst, Dehydration, Dyspnoea, Weakness, Malaise, Sore throat, Fever, Chills, Gastroenteritis, Blurred vision, Twitching/convulsions, Tingling/numbness, Dilated pupils, Constricted pupils, Difficulty swallowing/speaking/breathing, Rash, Itching of skin
labs_diagnostics: Isolation of suspected causative agent/s (refer to MOH guidelines) AND detailed risk assessment

name: Plague
category: moh,front
case_def: Animal disease of wild rodents, pets and Bragatha and is caused by the plague bacillus (Yersinia Pestis), a rod-shaped bacteria and the disease is transmitted to humans by the bites of fleas and flea-east private Rat (XenopsyllaCheopis) through droplets from people with pneumonic plague, dealing with fluids and tissues of infected animals, especially rodents.

name: Yellow fever
category: moh,front
case_def:
Acute phase is characterized by symptoms of fever, muscle pain and a private area in the back, headaches, trembling, loss of appetite, which may be accompanied by vomiting.
Toxic phase constitutes 15% of the patients ALWIL phase, where the re-fever reappeared within 24 hours with symptoms of infection various organs of the body, Calerqan, abdominal pain accompanied by vomiting, and bleeding from the mouth happens, nose, eyes or stomach, and may lead to failure sharp in the functions of the kidneys

name: Mumps
category: moh,front
case_def: Acute onset of painful swelling in one side or both sides of the gland Alinkavah or salivary glands and continue this swelling for two days or more without apparent reason for the swelling

name: Typhoid fever
category: moh,front
case_def:
Suspected case: a patient suffering from high temperature for more than three days with one of the following symptoms: headache, abdominal pain, diarrhea, constipation
Confirmed case: suspected case + isolate bacteria by bone marrow transplant or blood cultivation (during the first week) and the cultivation of urine and feces (after the first week)

name: Relapsing fever
category: moh,front

name: Brucellosis
category: moh,front
case_def:
Possible case: show symptoms of the disease and be a positive reaction to examine the Rose Bengal Test
Confirmed case: show symptoms of the disease and prove the laboratory examines Standard Tube Agglutination Test (STA) or Coombs Test or Isolation of the organism
labs_diagnostics: Measure serum frequency Titer

name: Leprosy
category: moh,front
case_def: Chronic and infectious disease affects the skin, nerves and mucous membrane surrounding the upper respiratory tract and eyes have been transmitted from one person to another but it is not highly contagious as the incubation period may extend from months to 20 years. Becomes infected person is not contagious within days of receiving treatment.
risk_factors: Close contact with someone with leprosy, Displacement, Overcrowding conditions
symptoms: Leprosy patches (can be pale or reddish or copper colored; flat or raised; do not itch; usually do not hurt; lack sensation to heat, touch or pain; can appear anywhere), Reddish or skin-colored nodules, Smooth and shiny diffuse thickening of skin without a loss of sensation, Numbness or tingling of the hands or feet, Weakness of the hands, feet or eyelids, Painful or tender nerves, Swelling of or lumps in the face or earlobes, Painless wounds or burns on the hands or feet

name: Typhus
category: moh,front
case_def: a person MOH experiences sudden headache, chills, high fever, prostration, coughing and severe muscular pain.  After 5 to 6 days, a macular skin eruption (dark spots) develop on the upper trunk and spreads to the rest of the body.
risk_factors: Cold, mountainous conditions, Overcrowded living conditions, Displacement, Exposure to lice
symptoms: Headache, Chills, High fever , Prostration, Coughing, Severe muscular pain, Macular skin eruption (dark spots) on upper trunk or other areas of the body)

After the passage of (2-5) days of the disease begins to evolve into shock and bleeding quickly and sudden

name: West Nile fever
category: moh,front
case_def:
Suspected case: Anyone with a history of the disease from exposure to an area where there are injuries West Nile fever and show it at least two of the following clinical symptoms: heat, muscle pain, joint pain, headache, fatigue, enlarged lymph glands or a skin rash
Confirmed case: Suspected case is in addition to a positive laboratory test of serum WNv IgM or significance rise in WNv IgG or which have a positive laboratory test of serum or spinal fluid WNv Nucleic Acid Testing
labs_diagnostics: Serum WNv IgM or significance rise in WNv IgG or which have a positive laboratory test of serum or spinal fluid WNv Nucleic Acid

name: Crimean Congo fever
category: moh,front
case_def: Disease starts quickly in a sudden and severe, where the temperature rises of 39-41 with a headache, chills and back pain, loss of appetite, stomach pain has temperature continues to rise 3-13 days or appear on two stages and much Aalm lower back at the two men with nausea and vomiting is linked eating, and congested face and neck with Oovema them, and congested throat and conjunctivitis and it changes the taste and smell mouth and red spots appear on the gums throat, and watery diarrhea occur with general weakness.

name: Rift Valley fever
category: moh,front
case_def:
Suspected case: anyone with a history of the disease from exposure to an area where there are injuries Rift Valley fever and the show has the following clinical symptoms:
Basic symptoms characterized by a feverish syndrome, flu-like, and muscle pain, and pain in the joints, and headache. Some patients from symptoms similar to meningitis suffer (stiff neck, sensitivity to light, loss of appetite, and vomiting)

name: Ebola
category: moh,front
case_def:
Suspected case: anyone with a sudden rise in temperature and at least three of the following symptoms: headache, vomiting, loss of appetite, diarrhea, lethargy, stomach pain, muscle joint pain, difficulty swallowing, difficulty breathing, bleeding, Ozubah (hicuup) in addition to the history of travel to an affected area of the disease within three weeks from the date of the onset of symptoms.
Confirmed case: suspected case + positive PCR (for a blood sample)

name: Influenza-like illness
category: moh,front
case_def: A person with an acute respiratory infection with measured fever >= 38'C and Coug and onset within the last 10 days.
labs_diagnostics:
Conventional or RT •  PCR OR viral antigen detection by immunofluorescence or enzyme immunoassay 
OR viral culture with second identification step to identify influenza viruses 
OR four-fold rise in antibody titre in paired acute and convalescent sera

name: Rickettsia
category: moh,front
case_def:

Confirmed case: suspected case + positive IgM

name: Arthropod-borne viral fevers and viral haemorrhagic fevers
category: for_child,cd,01. Certain infectious and parasitic diseases
case_def: Any person with fever AND maculopapular (non-vesicular) rash AND ONE of the following: cough,runny nose or red eyes; OR any person in whom a clinician suspects measles. A measles death is a death occurring within 30 days of onset of the rash.
symptoms: Age (children between 9 months and 5 years),overcrowding conditions,measles immunization coverage rate known to be <80% in area of origin/residence,malnutrition
labs_diagnostics: High fever,rash,runny nose,cough,conjunctivitis,Koplik spots (small white spots on buccal mucosa),red maculopapular (blotchy) rash 3 to 7 days after onset starting behind the ears and hairline
column19: History of fever and rash with at least one of the following: cough,coryza,conjunctivitis. OR observation of Koplik spots OR positive measles IgM antibodies test or isolation of measles RNA from respiratory specimens.

name: Viral infections characterized by skin and mucous membrane lesions
category: for_child,cd,01. Certain infectious and parasitic diseases

name: Viral hepatitis
category: for_child,cd,01. Certain infectious and parasitic diseases
case_def: Any person with acute onset of jaundice (yellowing of whites of eyes or skin or dark/brown urine) AND severe illness with or without fever AND the absence of any known precipitating factors. Acute hepatitis often presents as acute jaundice syndrome.
symptoms: Endemic Hepatitis A,contaminated water sources,contaminated food sources
labs_diagnostics: Asymptomatic,jaundice,dark urine,anorexia,malaise,extreme fatigue,pain in upper right quadrant
column19: Sporadic cases of acute jaundice with no or moderate fever are generally due to acute viral hepatitis (Hepatitis A,B,C or E),especially in children and young adults. Careful clinical examination can detect other causes of jaundice requiring specific treatment.

name: Human immunodeficiency virus [HIV] disease
category: for_child,cd,01. Certain infectious and parasitic diseases
case_def: For adults and children 18 months and older,persons have a positive HIV antibody test (rapid or laboratory-based enzyme immunoassay) confirmed by a second HIV antibody test (rapid or laboratory-based enzyme immunoassay) relying on different antigens or of different operating characteristics. For children younger than 18 months,a positive virological test for HIV or its components (HIV-RNA or HIV-DNA or ultrasensitive HIV p24 antigen) confirmed by a second virological test obtained from a separate determination taken more than 4 weeks after birth. Clinical staging is utilized to establish stage of HIV infection.
symptoms: Unprotected vaginal and/or anal sex,sharing of drug injection equipment,breastfeeding with unknown or HIV-positive status
labs_diagnostics: See link for WHO HIV staging
column19: For adults and children 18 months and older,persons have a positive HIV antibody test (rapid or laboratory-based enzyme immunoassay) confirmed by a second HIV antibody test (rapid or laboratory-based enzyme immunoassay) relying on different antigens or of different operating characteristics. For children younger than 18 months,a positive virological test for HIV or its components (HIV-RNA or HIV-DNA or ultrasensitive HIV p24 antigen) confirmed by a second virological test obtained from a separate determination taken more than 4 weeks after birth.

name: Moderate To Severe Depression
category: mhgap
symptoms: Depressed mood, Loss of interest or pleasure in activities that are normally pleasurable, Decreased energy or easily fatigued, None of the above, Reduced concentration and attention, Reduced self-esteem and self-confidence, Ideas of guilt and unworthiness, Bleak and pessimistic view of the future, Ideas or acts of self-harm or suicide, Disturbed sleep, Diminished appetite
labs_diagnostics:
•  Psychoeducation
•  Address current psychosocial stressors
•  Reactivate social networks
•  Consider antidepressants
•  If available, consider interpersonal therapy, behavioural activation or cognitive behavioural therapy
•  If available, consider adjunct treatments: structured physical activity programme, relaxation training or problem-solving treatment
•  DO NOT manage the complaint with injections or other ineffective treatments (e.g. vitamins).
•  Offer regular follow-up

name: Acute Psychosis
category: mhgap
symptoms: Incoherent or irrelevant speech, Delusions (a false firmly held belief or suspicion), Hallucinations (hearing voices or seeing things that are not there), Withdrawal, agitation, disorganized behaviour, Beliefs that thoughts are being inserted or broadcast from one's mind, Social withdrawal and neglect of usual responsibilities
labs_diagnostics:
•  Provide education to the person and carers about psychosis and its treatment
•  Begin antipsychotic medication
•  If available, provide psychological and social interventions, such as family therapy or social skills therapy
•  Facilitate rehabilitation
•  Provide regular follow-up
•  Maintain realistic hope and optimism

DO NOT prescribe anticholinergic medication routinely to prevent antipsychotic side-effects

name: Chronic Psychosis
category: mhgap
symptoms: Incoherent or irrelevant speech, Delusions (a false firmly held belief or suspicion), Hallucinations (hearing voices or seeing things that are not there), Withdrawal, agitation, disorganized behaviour, Beliefs that thoughts are being inserted or broadcast from one's mind, Social withdrawal and neglect of usual responsibilities
labs_diagnostics:
•  Provide education to the person and carers

IF THE PERSON IS NOT ON ANY TREATMENT, START TREATMENT AS FOR ACUTE PSYCHOTIC EPISODE

•  Review and ensure treatment adherence
•  If the person is not responding adequately, consider increasing current medication or changing it.
•  If available, provide psychological and social interventions such as family therapy or social skills therapy. Consider adding a psychosocial intervention not offered earlier, e.g. cognitive behavioural therapy if available
•  Provide regular follow-up
•  Maintain realistic hope and optimism
•  Facilitate rehabilitation

name: Mania
category: mhgap
symptoms: Elevated, expansive or irritable mood, Increased activity, restlessness, excitement, Increased talkativeness, Loss of normal social inhibitions, Decreased need for sleep, Inflated self-esteem, Distractibility, Elevated sexual energy or sexual indiscretion, None of the above, Loss of or impaired consciousness
labs_diagnostics:
•  Begin treatment of acute mania with lithium, valproate, carbamazepine or with antipsychotics
•  Consider a short-term benzodiazepine (such as diazepam) for behavioural disturbance or agitation
•  Discontinue any antidepressants
•  Advise the person to modify lifestyle; provide information about bipolar disorder and its treatment
•  Provide regular follow-up

name: Bipolar Depression
category: mhgap
symptoms: Elevated, expansive or irritable mood, Increased activity, restlessness, excitement, Increased talkativeness, Loss of normal social inhibitions, Decreased need for sleep, Inflated self-esteem, Distractibility, Elevated sexual energy or sexual indiscretion, None of the above, Loss of or impaired consciousness
labs_diagnostics:
•  Begin treatment with a mood-stabilizer
•  Consider antidepressant combined with mood stabilizer for moderate / severe depression
•  Inform the person about the risk of switching to mania before starting antidepressant medication
•  Advise the person to modify lifestyle; provide information about bipolar disorder and its treatment
•  Reactivate social networks
•  If available, consider psychological interventions
•  Pursue rehabilitation, including appropriate economic and educational activities, using formal and informal systems
•  Provide regular follow-up

name: Bipolar Depression Between Episodes
category: mhgap
symptoms: Elevated, expansive or irritable mood, Increased activity, restlessness, excitement, Increased talkativeness, Loss of normal social inhibitions, Decreased need for sleep, Inflated self-esteem, Distractibility, Elevated sexual energy or sexual indiscretion, None of the above, Loss of or impaired consciousness
labs_diagnostics:
•  If the person is not on a mood stabilizer then begin one
•  Advise person to modify lifestyle; provide information about bipolar disorder and its treatment
•  Reactivate social networks
•  Pursue rehabilitation, including appropriate economic and educational activities, using formal and informal systems
•  Provide regular follow-up; monitor side-effects and adherence

name: Non-Convulsive Seizures Or Other Medical Condition
category: mhgap
symptoms: Stiffness, rigidity lasting longer than 1 - 2 minute, Convulsive movements lasting longer than 1 - 2 minute, Tongue bite or self-injury, Incontinence of urine and / or faeces, After the abnormal movement: any fatigue, sleepiness, headache or muscles aches, Focal - starts in one part of the body, Prolonged - more than 15 minutes, Repetitive - more than 1 episode during the current illness
labs_diagnostics:
•  In case of recurrent episodes, CONSULT A SPECIALIST
•  Follow up after 3 months

name: Acute Aetiology
category: mhgap
symptoms: Stiffness, rigidity lasting longer than 1 - 2 minute, Convulsive movements lasting longer than 1 - 2 minute, Tongue bite or self-injury, Incontinence of urine and / or faeces, After the abnormal movement: any fatigue, sleepiness, headache or muscles aches, Focal - starts in one part of the body, Prolonged - more than 15 minutes, Repetitive - more than 1 episode during the current illness
labs_diagnostics:
•  Treat the medical condition
•  Antiepileptic maintenance treatment is not required
•  Follow up after 3 months to assess if the person has epilepsy

name: Complex Febrile Disease
category: mhgap
symptoms: Stiffness, rigidity lasting longer than 1 - 2 minute, Convulsive movements lasting longer than 1 - 2 minute, Tongue bite or self-injury, Incontinence of urine and / or faeces, After the abnormal movement: any fatigue, sleepiness, headache or muscles aches, Focal - starts in one part of the body, Prolonged - more than 15 minutes, Repetitive - more than 1 episode during the current illness
labs_diagnostics:
•  Refer for hospital admission.
•  Look for neuroinfection (suspect cerebral malaria in high endemic settings)
•  Follow up

name: Simple Febrile Seizure
category: mhgap
symptoms: Stiffness, rigidity lasting longer than 1 - 2 minute, Convulsive movements lasting longer than 1 - 2 minute, Tongue bite or self-injury, Incontinence of urine and / or faeces, After the abnormal movement: any fatigue, sleepiness, headache or muscles aches, Focal - starts in one part of the body, Prolonged - more than 15 minutes, Repetitive - more than 1 episode during the current illness
labs_diagnostics:
•  Manage fever and look for its cause according to the local IMCI guidelines
•  Observe for 24 hours
•  Follow up

name: Epilepsy
category: mhgap
symptoms: Stiffness, rigidity lasting longer than 1 - 2 minute, Convulsive movements lasting longer than 1 - 2 minute, Tongue bite or self-injury, Incontinence of urine and / or faeces, After the abnormal movement: any fatigue, sleepiness, headache or muscles aches, Focal - starts in one part of the body, Prolonged - more than 15 minutes, Repetitive - more than 1 episode during the current illness
labs_diagnostics:
•  Initiate antiepileptic drug phenobarbital, phenytoin, carbamazepine or valproate
•  Educate about condition, lifestyle and safety issues, and importance of adherence and regular follow-up
•  Follow up regularly

labs_diagnostics: •  CONSULT A SPECIALIST

name: Dementia
category: mhgap
symptoms: Problems with memory and orientation, Mood or behavioural problems , Loss of emotional control, Difficulties in carrying out usual activities
labs_diagnostics: •  CONSULT A SPECIALIST

name: Alcohol Intoxication
category: mhgap
symptoms: A strong desire or sense of compulsion to take alcohol, Difficulties in controlling alcohol use in terms of its onset, termination or levels of use, A physiological withdrawal state when alcohol use has ceased or been reduced, as shown by the characteristic withdrawal syndrome for alcohol; or use of the same (or a closely related) substance with the intention of relieving or avoiding withdrawal symptoms, Evidence of tolerance, such that increased doses of alcohol are required in order to achieve effects originally produced by lower doses, Progressive neglect of alternative pleasures or interests because of alcohol use, increased amount of time necessary to obtain or take alcohol or to recover from its effects, Alcohol use persisting despite clear evidence of overtly harmful consequences, such as harm to the liver, depressive mood states, or impairment of cognitive functioning
labs_diagnostics:
•  State clearly the results of alcohol use assessment and explain the links between this level of alcohol use, the person's health problems, and the short-term and long-term risks of continuing use at the current level
•  Ask about other substance use
•  Have a short discussion about the person's reasons for their alcohol use
•  State clearly the recommendation to either cut down to safer levels or stop using alcohol completely and your willingness to help the person to do so
•  If the person is willing to try to cut down or stop using alcohol, then discuss ways of
achieving this objective
•  If not, communicate confidently that it is possible to stop or reduce hazardous or harmful alcohol use and encourage the person to come back if he or she wants to discuss the issue further
•  Follow up at the next opportunity
•  Seek specialist advice as needed for people with ongoing harmful use of alcohol MOH have failed to respond to brief interventions

name: Alcohol Withdrawal
category: mhgap
symptoms: A strong desire or sense of compulsion to take alcohol, Difficulties in controlling alcohol use in terms of its onset, termination or levels of use, A physiological withdrawal state when alcohol use has ceased or been reduced, as shown by the characteristic withdrawal syndrome for alcohol; or use of the same (or a closely related) substance with the intention of relieving or avoiding withdrawal symptoms, Evidence of tolerance, such that increased doses of alcohol are required in order to achieve effects originally produced by lower doses, Progressive neglect of alternative pleasures or interests because of alcohol use, increased amount of time necessary to obtain or take alcohol or to recover from its effects, Alcohol use persisting despite clear evidence of overtly harmful consequences, such as harm to the liver, depressive mood states, or impairment of cognitive functioning
labs_diagnostics:
•  Treat immediately with diazepam
•  Treat in hospital or detoxification centre if available

If withdrawal is complicated by delirium:
•  Treat the withdrawal with diazepam
•  Manage in a safe environment
•  Keep well hydrated
•  If delirium or hallucinations persist despite treatment of other withdrawal symptoms, then consider using antipsychotics such as haloperidol 2.5 •  5 mg orally up to 3 times daily

If withdrawal is complicated by a seizure, treat with diazepam in the first instance and do not use anticonvulsants to prevent further seizures

name: Harmful Use Of Alcohol
category: mhgap
symptoms: A strong desire or sense of compulsion to take alcohol, Difficulties in controlling alcohol use in terms of its onset, termination or levels of use, A physiological withdrawal state when alcohol use has ceased or been reduced, as shown by the characteristic withdrawal syndrome for alcohol; or use of the same (or a closely related) substance with the intention of relieving or avoiding withdrawal symptoms, Evidence of tolerance, such that increased doses of alcohol are required in order to achieve effects originally produced by lower doses, Progressive neglect of alternative pleasures or interests because of alcohol use, increased amount of time necessary to obtain or take alcohol or to recover from its effects, Alcohol use persisting despite clear evidence of overtly harmful consequences, such as harm to the liver, depressive mood states, or impairment of cognitive functioning
labs_diagnostics:
•  State clearly the results of alcohol use assessment and explain the links between this level of alcohol use, the person's health problems, and the short-term and long-term risks of continuing use at the current level
•  Ask about other substance use
•  Have a short discussion about the person's reasons for their alcohol use
•  State clearly the recommendation to either cut down to safer levels or stop using alcohol completely and your willingness to help the person to do so
•  If the person is willing to try to cut down or stop using alcohol, then discuss ways of
achieving this objective
•  If not, communicate confidently that it is possible to stop or reduce hazardous or harmful alcohol use and encourage the person to come back if he or she wants to discuss the issue further
•  Follow up at the next opportunity
•  Seek specialist advice as needed for people with ongoing harmful use of alcohol MOH have failed to respond to brief interventions

name: Alcohol Dependence
category: mhgap
symptoms: A strong desire or sense of compulsion to take alcohol, Difficulties in controlling alcohol use in terms of its onset, termination or levels of use, A physiological withdrawal state when alcohol use has ceased or been reduced, as shown by the characteristic withdrawal syndrome for alcohol; or use of the same (or a closely related) substance with the intention of relieving or avoiding withdrawal symptoms, Evidence of tolerance, such that increased doses of alcohol are required in order to achieve effects originally produced by lower doses, Progressive neglect of alternative pleasures or interests because of alcohol use, increased amount of time necessary to obtain or take alcohol or to recover from its effects, Alcohol use persisting despite clear evidence of overtly harmful consequences, such as harm to the liver, depressive mood states, or impairment of cognitive functioning
labs_diagnostics:
•  State clearly the results of the assessment, and explain both the short-term and long-term risks of continuing use at the current level
•  Have a short discussion about the person's motivations for their alcohol use
•  Advise complete cessation of alcohol
•  Advise daily consumption of thiamine 100 mg
•  If the person is willing to try to stop using alcohol, facilitate alcohol cessation.
•  Determine the appropriate setting to cease alcohol
•  Plan the cessation of alcohol
•  Arrange detoxification if necessary
•  During detoxification, treat withdrawal symptoms with diazepam
•  After detoxification, prevent relapse with medication (naltrexone, acamprosate or disulfiram), if available
•  Assess and treat any medical or psychiatric co-morbidity, ideally after 2 •  3 weeks of abstinence as some problems will resolve with abstinence.
•  Consider referral to a self-help group (such as Alcoholics Anonymous), or a residential therapeutic community
•  DO NOT administer punishment in the name of treatment
•  Address housing and employment needs
•  Provide information and support to person, carers and family members
•  If available, provide psychosocial interventions such as family counselling or therapy, problem-solving counselling or therapy, cognitive behavioural therapy, motivational enhancement therapy, or contingency management therapy
•  Consider referral to a specialized treatment facility
•  Follow up as needed, frequently initially
•  Seek specialist support as needed

name: Opioid Or Other Sedative Overdose
category: mhgap
symptoms: Strong desire or sense of compulsion to take drugs, Difficulties in controlling drug use in terms of its onset, termination or levels of use, A physiological withdrawal state when drug use has ceased or been reduced, as shown by the characteristic drug-withdrawal syndrome; or use of the same (or a closely related) substance with the intention of relieving or avoiding withdrawal symptoms, Evidence of tolerance, such that increased doses of the substance are required in order to achieve effects originally produced by lower doses, Progressive neglect of alternative pleasures or interests because of drug use, increased amount of time necessary to obtain or take drug or to recover from its effects, Drug use persisting, despite clear evidence of overtly harmful consequences
labs_diagnostics:
If:
•  Respiratory rate< 10 OR
•  Oxygen saturation< 92 %

Then:
•  Treat airway, breathing and circulation
•  Naloxone 0.4 mg subcutaneous, i.m. or i.v. (for opioid overdose •  but ineffective for other sedative overdose),repeat if necessary
•  Observe for 1 •  2 hours after naloxone administration
•  For overdoses due to long acting opioids •  transport to hospital for naloxone infusion or ventilatory support

If unresponsive to naloxone
•  Provide airway and ventilatory support and transport to hospital

name: Cocaine Or Amphetamine-Type Stimulant Intoxication Or Overdose
category: mhgap
symptoms: Strong desire or sense of compulsion to take drugs, Difficulties in controlling drug use in terms of its onset, termination or levels of use, A physiological withdrawal state when drug use has ceased or been reduced, as shown by the characteristic drug-withdrawal syndrome; or use of the same (or a closely related) substance with the intention of relieving or avoiding withdrawal symptoms, Evidence of tolerance, such that increased doses of the substance are required in order to achieve effects originally produced by lower doses, Progressive neglect of alternative pleasures or interests because of drug use, increased amount of time necessary to obtain or take drug or to recover from its effects, Drug use persisting, despite clear evidence of overtly harmful consequences
labs_diagnostics:
•  Give diazepam in titrated doses until the person is calm and lightly sedated
•  If psychotic symptoms do not respond to benzodiazepines, then consider using short-term •  antipsychotics
•  DO NOT commence long-term antipsychotics.loading
•  Monitor blood pressure, pulse rate, respiratory rate, temperature every 2 •  4 hours
•  If the person complains of chest pain, if tachyarrhythmias are present or if the person becomes violent or unmanageable, transfer the person to hospital
•  During the post-intoxication phase •  be alert for suicidal thoughts or actions

name: Opioid Withdrawal
category: mhgap
symptoms: Strong desire or sense of compulsion to take drugs, Difficulties in controlling drug use in terms of its onset, termination or levels of use, A physiological withdrawal state when drug use has ceased or been reduced, as shown by the characteristic drug-withdrawal syndrome; or use of the same (or a closely related) substance with the intention of relieving or avoiding withdrawal symptoms, Evidence of tolerance, such that increased doses of the substance are required in order to achieve effects originally produced by lower doses, Progressive neglect of alternative pleasures or interests because of drug use, increased amount of time necessary to obtain or take drug or to recover from its effects, Drug use persisting, despite clear evidence of overtly harmful consequences
labs_diagnostics:
•  Treat with reducing doses of opioids (methadone, buprenorphine) or alpha-adrenergic agents (clonidine, lofexidine) using either supervised dosing or daily dispensing
•  Treat specifi c symptoms as needed (diarrhoea, vomiting, muscle pain, insomnia)
•  Consider starting opioid agonist maintenance treatment
•  Oral or i.v. rehydration, if necessary

name: Drug Dependence
category: mhgap
symptoms: Strong desire or sense of compulsion to take drugs, Difficulties in controlling drug use in terms of its onset, termination or levels of use, A physiological withdrawal state when drug use has ceased or been reduced, as shown by the characteristic drug-withdrawal syndrome; or use of the same (or a closely related) substance with the intention of relieving or avoiding withdrawal symptoms, Evidence of tolerance, such that increased doses of the substance are required in order to achieve effects originally produced by lower doses, Progressive neglect of alternative pleasures or interests because of drug use, increased amount of time necessary to obtain or take drug or to recover from its effects, Drug use persisting, despite clear evidence of overtly harmful consequences
labs_diagnostics:
•  State clearly the diagnosis and inform about the risks of short-term and long-term harm.
•  Explore the person's reasons for their drug use, using brief intervention techniques
•  Advise the person to stop using the substance completely and indicate the intention to support the person in doing so
•  Ask the person if they are ready to try to stop using the substance

Cannabis or Stimulant Dependence
•  Provide a more intensive brief intervention (i.e., up to 3 sessions, each lasting up to 45 minutes)
•  Treat withdrawal symptoms
•  Arrange detoxification service if necessary

Opioid dependence
•  Assess severity of dependence
•  In most cases, advise opioid agonist maintenance treatment (also known as opioid-substitutiontherapy, OST). Provide or refer for OST, if available
•  Arrange planned detoxification if requested

Benzodiazepine dependence
•  Gradual reduction of benzodiazepines with supervised dispensing or more rapid reduction ofbenzodiazepines in an in-patient setting

IN ALL CASES
•  Consider referral to self-help groups, and rehabilitation / therapeutic communities
•  Address housing and employment needs
•  Provide information and support to person, carers and family members
•  If available, provide psychosocial interventions, such as family counselling or therapy, problem-solving counselling or therapy, cognitive behavioural therapy, motivational enhancement therapy, contingency management therapy

name: Risk Of Self-Harm Or Suicide
category: mhgap
symptoms: Strong desire or sense of compulsion to take drugs, Difficulties in controlling drug use in terms of its onset, termination or levels of use, A physiological withdrawal state when drug use has ceased or been reduced, as shown by the characteristic drug-withdrawal syndrome; or use of the same (or a closely related) substance with the intention of relieving or avoiding withdrawal symptoms, Evidence of tolerance, such that increased doses of the substance are required in order to achieve effects originally produced by lower doses, Progressive neglect of alternative pleasures or interests because of drug use, increased amount of time necessary to obtain or take drug or to recover from its effects, Drug use persisting, despite clear evidence of overtly harmful consequences
labs_diagnostics:
If person requires urgent medical treatment for act of self-harm
•  Medically treat injury or poisoning.loading
•  If Acute Pesticide Intoxication, follow Pesticide Intoxication Management

In all cases:
•  Place the person in a secure and supportive environment at the health facility while being assessed (do not leave them alone)
•  Care for the person with self-harm
•  Offer and activate psychosocial support
•  Consult mental health specialist if available
•  Maintain regular contact and follow-up

name: Severe Pneumonia Or Very Severe Disease
category: imci
symptoms: Chest indrawing, Stridor, Wheezing, None of the above
labs_diagnostics:
•  Give first dose of an appropriate antibiotic 
•  Refer URGENTLY to hospital

name: Pneumonia
category: imci
symptoms: Chest indrawing, Stridor, Wheezing, None of the above
labs_diagnostics:
•  Give oral Amoxicillin for 5 days
•  If wheezing (or disappeared after rapidly acting bronchodilator) give an inhaled bronchodilator for 5 days
•  If chest indrawing in HIV exposed/infected child, give first dose of amoxicillin and refer.
•  Soothe the throat and relieve the cough with a safe remedy
•  If coughing for more than 14 days or recurrent wheeze, refer for possible TB or asthma assessment
•  Advise mother when to return immediately Follow-up in 3 days 
•  Refer URGENTLY to hospital

name: Cough Or Cold
category: imci
symptoms: Chest indrawing, Stridor, Wheezing, None of the above
labs_diagnostics:
•  If wheezing (or disappeared after rapidly acting bronchodilator) give an inhaled bronchodilator for 5 days
•  Soothe the throat and relieve the cough with a safe remedy
•  If coughing for more than 14 days or recurrent wheezing, refer for possible TB or asthma assessment
•  Advise mother when to return immediately Follow-up in 5 days if not improving

name: Severe Dehydration
category: imci
symptoms: Duration, Skin pinch, is lethargic or unconscious, is restless and irritable, is not able to drink or drinking poorly, is drinking eagerly, thirsty
labs_diagnostics:
•  If child has no other severe classification:
•  Give fluid for severe dehydration (Plan C)

OR

•  If child also has another severe classification:
•  Refer URGENTLY to hospital with mother giving frequent sips of ORS on the way Advise the mother to continue breastfeeding
•  If child is 2 years or older and there is cholera in your area, give antibiotic for cholera

name: Some Dehydration
category: imci
symptoms: Duration, Skin pinch, is lethargic or unconscious, is restless and irritable, is not able to drink or drinking poorly, is drinking eagerly, thirsty
labs_diagnostics:
•  Give fluid, zinc supplements, and food for some dehydration (Plan B)
•  If child also has a severe classification:
•  Refer URGENTLY to hospital with mother giving frequent sips of ORS on the way  
•  Advise the mother to continue breastfeeding
•  Advise mother when to return immediately 
•  Follow-up in 5 days if not improving

name: Severe Persistent Diarrhoea
category: imci
symptoms: Duration, Skin pinch, is lethargic or unconscious, is restless and irritable, is not able to drink or drinking poorly, is drinking eagerly, thirsty
labs_diagnostics:
•  Treat dehydration before referral unless the child has another severe classification
•  Refer to hospital

name: Persistent Diarrhoea
category: imci
symptoms: Duration, Skin pinch, is lethargic or unconscious, is restless and irritable, is not able to drink or drinking poorly, is drinking eagerly, thirsty
labs_diagnostics:
•   Advise the mother on feeding a child MOH has PERSISTENT DIARRHOEA
•   Give multivitamins and minerals (including zinc) for 14 days 
•   Follow-up in 5 days

name: Dysentery
category: imci
symptoms: blood in the stool
labs_diagnostics:
•  Give ciprofloxacin for 3 days
•  Follow-up in 3 days

name: Very Severe Febrile Disease
category: imci

•  Give first dose of an appropriate antibiotic

name: Severe Complicated Measles
category: imci
symptoms: Duration (Less than seven days, More than seven days), Has a stiff neck, Has a runny nose, Has any bacterial cause of infection, Has a generalised rash, Has cough, runny nose or red eyes

•  Give one dose of paracetamol in clinic for high fever (38.5 oC or above)

•  Follow-up in 2 days if fever persists

name: Measles With Eye Or Mouth Complications
category: imci

name: Measles
category: imci

•  Advise mother when to return immediately

name: Severe Anaemia
category: imci
symptoms: Severe pallor, Some pallor
labs_diagnostics: •  Refer URGENTLY to hopsital

name: Anaemia
category: imci
symptoms: Severe pallor, Some pallor
labs_diagnostics:
•  Give iron
 •  Give mebendazole if child is 1 year or older and has not had a dose in the previous 6 months 
 •  Advise mother when to return immediately

name: Confirmed HIV Infection
category: imci
labs_diagnostics:
•  Initiate ART treatment and HIV care
